In this proclamation, President Barack Obama declares February 2012 as National African American History Month. He highlights the resilience and perseverance of African Americans throughout history, emphasizing their fight for freedom and equality. The theme for this year's celebration is "Black Women in American Culture and History," recognizing the important role African American women have played in shaping the nation. Obama acknowledges their contributions in various fields, from activism to arts and culture. He also calls for continued efforts to ensure equal opportunities for all Americans. The proclamation encourages public officials, educators, librarians, and the general public to observe the month with appropriate programs and activities.